    slug: "isaayiat-tajziyah-aur-mutaliyah",
    description: `Isaayiat — Tajziyah aur Mutaliyah is an Urdu-language academic and analytical book that provides a detailed study of the Book of Isaiah (Isaayiat) from the Biblical tradition, presenting a critical examination, division (tajziyah), and analytical study (mutaliyah) of this major prophetic text from the perspective of Islamic scholarship and comparative religion. The title reflects the book's dual approach: a systematic division and categorization of the content of Isaiah into its constituent themes, historical contexts, and literary structures (tajziyah), followed by an in-depth analytical study that examines the theological claims, historical accuracy, and internal consistency of the text (mutaliyah). This work belongs to the genre of Urdu-language Islamic comparative religion literature that engages critically with non-Islamic scriptures, providing Muslim readers with scholarly tools for understanding and evaluating the claims of other religious traditions.

The book begins with an introduction to the Book of Isaiah, covering its historical background, authorship debates, the traditional division of the book into First Isaiah (chapters 1-39), Deutero-Isaiah (chapters 40-55), and Trito-Isaiah (chapters 56-66), and the scholarly consensus and disagreements regarding when and by whom these sections were composed. The author provides a detailed analysis of the historical context of each section, explaining the political and religious situation of the Kingdom of Judah and Israel during the periods in which the various parts of Isaiah were composed, and how these historical circumstances influenced the content and tone of the prophecies. The book pays particular attention to the messianic prophecies contained in Isaiah, which are frequently cited by Christian theologians as predictions of Jesus Christ, and provides an Islamic perspective on these passages, examining whether the descriptions in Isaiah more accurately correspond to the profile of the Prophet Muhammad (peace be upon him) as understood in Islamic tradition.

The analytical section of the book applies the tools of textual criticism, historical analysis, and theological evaluation to the Book of Isaiah, identifying instances where the text contains apparent contradictions, internal inconsistencies, or theological positions that conflict with the Islamic understanding of divine revelation. The author discusses the concept of prophethood in Isaiah compared to the Islamic concept of nubuwwah, the nature of God as portrayed in Isaiah compared to the Islamic understanding of Allah's attributes, and the treatment of covenant, law, and salvation in Isaiah compared to the Quranic framework. The book also addresses the way Isaiah has been interpreted and utilized in Jewish and Christian theological traditions, comparing these interpretations with the Islamic perspective. The Urdu prose is academic and well-researched, with extensive references to primary and secondary sources. This book is a valuable resource for students of comparative religion, Islamic dawah workers who engage in interfaith dialogue, and Urdu-speaking scholars who want to develop a critical understanding of one of the most important texts in the Judeo-Christian tradition.`,
    metaDescription: "Isaayiat Tajziyah aur Mutaliyah is an Urdu critical study of the Biblical Isaiah. Analyzes themes and messianic prophecies from an Islamic perspective."
