    slug: "isharon-ki-zuban-mai-namaz",
    description: `Isharon ki Zuban mai Namaz is an Urdu-language instructional book that teaches the method of performing the Islamic prayer (salah) using sign language and gestures (isharon ki zuban), making the essential acts of worship accessible to deaf and hearing-impaired Muslims who communicate primarily through sign language. The book addresses a critical need within the Muslim community, as deaf and hearing-impaired individuals often face significant barriers to learning the correct method of performing salah due to the reliance of most Islamic educational materials on verbal instruction and auditory cues. By adapting the teaching of salah into a visual and gestural format, this book ensures that deaf Muslims can perform their daily prayers with the same level of knowledge, confidence, and correctness as their hearing counterparts.

The book provides a comprehensive step-by-step guide to performing the five daily obligatory prayers — Fajr, Dhuhr, Asr, Maghrib, and Isha — using detailed illustrations and descriptions of the specific hand signs, body movements, and facial expressions that correspond to each part of the prayer. For each element of the prayer, from the opening takbir (Allahu Akbar) to the final salam, the book shows the appropriate sign language gesture that accompanies the spoken words, allowing deaf Muslims to express the verbal components of the prayer through physical signs. The book covers the physical postures of salah — standing (qiyam), bowing (ruku), prostration (sujud), and sitting (jalsa) — with particular attention to the proper alignment of the body, the placement of the hands, and the sequence of movements, all presented in a visual format that can be easily followed by readers who rely on visual rather than auditory learning.

Beyond the obligatory prayers, the book also covers the method of performing the funeral prayer (salat al-janazah), the Eid prayer (salat al-Eid), the Taraweeh prayers of Ramadan, and the voluntary prayers (nawafil) including the Witr prayer and the Tahajjud night prayer. Each type of prayer is presented with its own set of visual instructions and sign language adaptations. The book also includes guidance on the prerequisites of salah, such as the conditions of wudu (ablution), the times of the five daily prayers, the direction of the Qiblah, and the proper covering of the body (awrah), all explained through illustrations and simple Urdu text. The book serves as an essential resource for deaf and hearing-impaired Muslims, for special education teachers in Islamic schools, for imams and religious leaders who want to make their mosques more inclusive, and for the family members of deaf Muslims who want to support their loved ones in their religious practice. The visual approach of the book also makes it useful as a supplementary teaching tool for young children who are learning to pray, regardless of their hearing ability.`,
    metaDescription: "Isharon ki Zuban mai Namaz is an Urdu book teaching salah through sign language for deaf Muslims. Covers five daily prayers, wudu, and voluntary prayers."
